@Massimo 

Maine and Nebraska base their electoral count on districts (representative districts), rather than electoral voters.

Each electoral vote is based on representatives (based on population) plus the number of senators (2 per state)

@Luke 

I'm glad you're engaged in our democracy from a country around the world.

To answer your question, electoral college votes are comprised of the # of representatives from each state PLUS the two senators in each state. In Ohio (a Great Lakes State), where I live, we have 16 representatives (Based on population), and two senators, meaning we have 18 electoral votes. States with smaller votes, like Alaska, have only one representative, and two senators (3 electoral votes). California is the most populated, and has the most electoral votes, with 53 representatives, and two senators.  In America, there are still questions on if the electoral college is still useful.

@Luke 

It also makes me me happy that you are interested in democracy in the United States. It interests me that people around the world have questions on what the United States does differently. 

To answer your fourth response for what is going on in the graphs from the article. What it basically means is that the blue states which is the democratic party have won by the electoral college (as Joshua explained). Joe Biden won the 2020 election which will make him president.

@Will Nebraska and Maine didn't have faithless electors, they just do the electoral college differently than the other 48 states. It's pretty cool!
Nebraska and Maine let each of their Congressional Districts choose one elector and then put the remaining two electoral college votes up to the state as a whole. So the people in Maine's 2nd Congressional District, along with getting to choose their Congressperson in the U.S. House of Representatives, got to choose how one of Maine's four electoral college votes got allocated. With that district being mostly rural and Republican, they gave their electoral college vote to Trump, unlike the rest of the state which voted for Biden. It's anomalies like these which make the electoral college hard to explain at times.
We won't know if there are any actual faithless electors until the electoral college meets in December.
